It is therefore unlikely that this Heraclitean kind of demonstration of the soul’s immortality (in Plat. Phaed. 70d-72a) conceals another doctrine: the παλαιὸς λόγος – often quoted concerning ancient myths – only pertains the anthropogonic and eschatological myth of the Orphics; 
                        if it might be supposed that this παλαιὸς λόγος has to be linked to a different form of religiosity, it would be possible to think of Eleusinian myths and rites (well known by Plato), but they – even though very familiar with the idea of the cyclicity of nature – do not provide for any cycle of the souls, in eschatological terms. 
                        The ultimate aim of the initiate is in fact the attainment of the beatitude in Hades – as opposed to the oblivion and shadow, threatened by the Olympian religiosity – but with no reference to a “return to generation” of souls.
